b'You don\xe2\x80\x99t need any special training to check your breasts, but sometimes you need a reminder of why it\xe2\x80\x99s so important\xe2\x80\xa6\xe2\xa0\x80
\xe2\xa0\x80
Meet Jon Turner :waving_hand:\xe2\xa0\x80
\xe2\xa0\x80
Jon, 45, a spokesperson and fundraiser for Breast Cancer Now, supported his late wife Rachel through her illness. He lives with their two children, Jessica, 12, and Freya, 9.\xe2\xa0\x80
\xe2\xa0\x80
\xe2\x80\x98Rach was accustomed to the lumps and bumps that were usual for her, so when she found an acorn-shaped lump while in the shower, she didn\xe2\x80\x99t panic. Three weeks later, it was still there. She was diagnosed with grade-three triple-negative invasive breast cancer \xe2\x80\x93 a very aggressive type of cancer. After surgery, the doctors confirmed that the cancer could never be cured as it had spread to her brain, lungs, bones and liver.\xe2\xa0\x80
\xe2\xa0\x80
We were devastated. In the three years that followed, we made the best of our time as a family. One day, Jessica asked, \xe2\x80\x9cWhat\xe2\x80\x99s going to happen to you?\xe2\x80\x9d and Rach answered, \xe2\x80\x9cI\xe2\x80\x99m going to heaven\xe2\x80\x9d.\xe2\xa0\x80
\xe2\xa0\x80
Rach died at the start of January 2018 with her family around her. I see her in my daughters every day \xe2\x80\x93 they have their mum\xe2\x80\x99s kindness, sensitivity and wicked sense of humour.\xe2\xa0\x80
\xe2\xa0\x80
After Rach died, I began running to deal with the grief. In 2019, I ran the London Marathon, raising \xc2\xa33,000 for Breast Cancer Now who had been our guiding light through the uncertainty that cancer brings. I knew that Rach was with me every step of the way.\xe2\xa0\x80
\xe2\xa0\x80
Early diagnosis can make a massive difference, so check yourself regularly is so important. Never think it can\xe2\x80\x99t happen to you.\xe2\x80\x99\xe2\xa0\x80
\xe2\xa0\x80
Head to the link in our bio for more info on Asda\xe2\x80\x99s Tickled Pink campaign.\xe2\xa0\x80
\xe2\xa0\x80
#BreastCancerAwarenessMonth #TickledPink #CheckYourBreasts #BeYourBreastFriend #Asda #BreastCancerNow'

b'You don\xe2\x80\x99t need any special training to check your breasts, but sometimes you need a reminder of why it is so important\xe2\x80\xa6\xe2\xa0\x80
This is Kris, founder of charity CoppaFeel \xe2\x80\x93 and this is her story.\xe2\xa0\x80
\xe2\xa0\x80
\xe2\x80\x98At 22, I found a hard lump in my boob. I had no idea how long it had been there or if it was normal for me. I was told it was hormonal, so it was devastating when, after three visits to my doctor, I was diagnosed with stage-four breast cancer at the age of 23. This is a secondary form of breast cancer, where cells from the primary tumour in the breast spread to other parts of the body. In my case, it was found in my spine.\xe2\xa0\x80
\xe2\xa0\x80
I wanted to educate people \xe2\x80\x93 and young people especially \xe2\x80\x93 about breast cancer, to let them know an earlier diagnosis means a higher chance of recovery, so in 2009 I founded CoppaFeel!\xe2\xa0\x80
\xe2\xa0\x80
We\xe2\x80\x99re so proud to be partnering with Tickled Pink. We want to expand our reach with people from all walks of life, empowering them to get to know their normal, check their boobs and pecs regularly, and act upon any changes. With Tickled Pink, we\xe2\x80\x99ll have the chance to make waves and save lives.\xe2\x80\x99\xe2\xa0\x80
\xe2\xa0\x80
Head to the link in our bio for more info on Asda\xe2\x80\x99s Tickled Pink campaign.\xe2\xa0\x80
\xe2\xa0\x80
#BreastCancerAwarenessMonth #TickledPink #CheckYourBreasts #BeYourBreastFriend #Asda #BreastCancerNow'

b'Our colleague Helen, who's currently being treated for breast cancer, is urging everyone to get behind our Tickled Pink charity campaign and says its message of encouraging people to regularly check themselves is so important.

Helen works alongside her husband Rob at our Thornaby store and was diagnosed last October when she found a lump as she made one of her routine checks. She said: "I've always been a supporter of Tickled Pink \xe2\x80\x93 I think the campaign is great. Raising awareness to everyone needs to be done. So many people think 'oh, it won't happen to me', but you just never know. Keep checking routinely and if you find anything unusual then definitely get it looked at straight away, as the earlier you do it the better your prognosis." Helen says the support of everyone at the store has been a huge help, in particular her friend Lynn, who was diagnosed with breast cancer in 2012 and has since made a great recovery. "Asda Thornaby is such a community store. We look our for each other and everyone sticks together. It's more like a second family. They've been fabulous."

Read Helen's full story here: https://bit.ly/2RWe3Ia

#ASDA #ASDATickledPink #BCAM #TickledPink #BreastCancer #BreastCancerAwareness #BreastCancerNow #CheckYourBreasts'

b"We\xe2\x80\x99re committed to helping make the local community around our stores a better place to live, work and grow up in \xe2\x80\x93 it's why we have a community champion in nearly 400 of our larger stores.

b'At Asda, now more than ever, we are committed to our role in feeding the nation, and supporting our customers and the communities we serve. Our stores are already supporting the amazing care homes in their local communities, like our Community Champion Danielle at Asda Bishop Auckland who has been donating baked treats to care homes in her community. Today our CEO Roger Burnley announced our plans to offer much needed support to the amazing care homes across the UK:\xe2\x80\x8b\xe2\xa0\x80
\xe2\xa0\x80
\xc2\xb7 We have emailed all 3,500 small care homes who are registered with Asda to offer a priority pass for online shopping with us, helping them get the food and essentials they need.\xe2\x80\x8b\xe2\xa0\x80
\xe2\xa0\x80
\xc2\xb7 From the middle of May we are also donating 250,000 medical-grade face masks to care homes, to help them keep their residents and workers safe.\xe2\x80\x8b\xe2\xa0\x80
\xe2\xa0\x80
\xc2\xb7 We are also still welcoming care home workers in our priority hours in store. They can shop first every Monday, Wednesday and Friday before 9am and for an exclusive browsing hour every Sunday before each store opens.\xe2\x80\x8b\xe2\xa0\x80
\xe2\xa0\x80
Thank you for your continued support \xe2\x80\x93 we are all in this together.'

b'This week we are proud to launch a dedicated volunteer shopping card to help the many people self-isolating and unable to go out to buy their shopping. With the support of millions of amazing volunteers, we\xe2\x80\x99ll be able to make sure these vulnerable customers have access to their shopping essentials. Customers can buy these shopping cards online, top up and give to their family member, friend, or NHS volunteer to pay for their shopping without the hassle of using cash or bank cards.\xe2\xa0\x80\n\xe2\xa0\x80\nThis also promotes a contactless way of shopping, essential for reducing risk to our self-isolating customers. It gives customers confidence that they don\xe2\x80\x99t need to share card details, whilst also reducing contact with volunteers who are helping to drop much needed essentials straight to the doorsteps of those in need, as safely as possible. These volunteer shopping cards can be bought at ASDA.com/volunteercard.'

b'We\xe2\x80\x99re donating \xc2\xa35 million to food charities FareShare and the Trussell Trust to help them support the most vulnerable people in our communities during the coronavirus outbreak.\n\nThe donation means they can provide meals to families in poverty impacted by coronavirus, as well as giving the 3,000 charities they in turn support the ability to access free food over the next three months as they fight to tackle the local impact of the virus. We\xe2\x80\x99re also investing in the logistics and support services that will allow FareShare and the Trussell Trust to support families through the crisis, including funding for telephone and online referrals, and food parcel delivering systems for people unable to afford food, as well as supporting the recruitment of 20,000 volunteers for food banks in the Trussell Trust network.'
b'We\xe2\x80\x99re all in this together.'

VEGAN CAULIFLOWER HOT BUFFALO 'WINGS' \xe2\xa0\x80
1. Mix together 50g plain flour, 20g cornflour, 1tsp onion granules, 1/2tsp dried thyme and some pepper.\xe2\xa0\x80
2. Cut a cauliflower into florets, toss in oil and coat in the flour mixture. \xe2\xa0\x80
3. Bake at 200C for 20 mins before drizzling with hot sauce and baking for another 10 mins. \xe2\xa0\x80
4. Serve with vegan sour cream or mayo.\xe2\xa0\x80
For all the ingredients visit Asda.com or pop into store.\xe2\xa0\x80

b'Looking for a healthier comfort food recipe? :spaghetti: This deliciously creamy veggie Butternut Squash and Spinach Gnocchi is a brilliant low fat, low salt dinner ready in under 25 minutes - Boom!\xe2\xa0\x80
\xe2\xa0\x80
BUTTERNUT SQUASH AND SPINACH GNOCCHI\xe2\xa0\x80
400g frozen butternut squash chunks\xe2\xa0\x80
1 clove garlic, chopped \xe2\xa0\x80
1 reduced-salt veg stock cube, made up to 300ml \xe2\xa0\x80
1/2 tbsp dried sage\xe2\xa0\x80
2tsp rapeseed oil\xe2\xa0\x80
500g pack Asda Gnocchi\xe2\xa0\x80
60g baby spinach\xe2\xa0\x80
2tbsp hazelnuts, chopped\xe2\xa0\x80
\xe2\xa0\x80
1. Put the squash, garlic, stock and sage in a pan; season with black pepper. Bring to a simmer and cook for 10-12 minutes until soft. Blitz with handheld blender until smooth.\xe2\xa0\x80
2. Meanwhile, heat the oil in a large nonstick frying pan. Fry the gnocchi for 6-8 mins on a low-medium heat until golden and crisp.\xe2\xa0\x80
3. Add the squash sauce to the gnocchi, stir through the spinach and cook until it has wilted. Divide evenly between 4 bowls, then scatter over the chopped hazelnuts before serving. \xe2\xa0\x80
\xe2\xa0\x80
